CommonFields.Title: Effects of silane functionalization on the properties of carbon nanotube/epoxy nanocomposites
Author: Ma, Peng Cheng
Kim, Jang-Kyo
Tang, Ben Zhong
CommonFields.Location: Department of Mechanical Engineering, The Hong Kong University of Science and Technology, Clear Water Bay, Kowloon, Hong Kong, PR China

Mixing.Description: The CNTs were dispersed in ethanol for 1          h
monomer epoxy was added to the CNT mixture, and the          mixture was ultrasonicated for 1 h at 80C

ChooseParameter.Other: The mixture was then outgassed at 80C for 5 h to eliminate the        entrapped air and the remaining ethanol

Additive.Description: The m-PDA hardener was added into the mixture in the          ratio of 14.5:100 by weight

MoldingInfo.Description: The composite was moulded into a flat plate and cured            at 80C for 2 h

Heating.Description: Following moulding, the composite was post cured at          150C for 2 h

Scanning_Electron_Microscopy.Description: SEM was employed to examine the dispersion states of CNTs      in the matrix and the fracture morphologies of CNT/epoxy      nanocomposites

Dynamic_Mechanical_Analysis.Description: The samples with dimensions 20 mm long x 3 mm wide x 1 mm      thick were tested in a three point bending mode from 30 to 170C at a      heating rate of 10C/min and a frequency of 1.0 Hz within a nitrogen      atmosphere. The glass transition temperatures, Tg, of nanocomposites      were also determined from the maxima of the tan-delta acquired from the      DMA

Thermogravimetric_Analysis.Description: Specimens were heated from ambient to 800C at a heating      rate of 10C/min in the nitrogen flow

Electrometry.Description: The bulk electrical conductivity of nanocomposites was      measured at room temperature based on the four-probe method using      specimens of dimensions 10 mm square x 1 mm in thickness on a      resistivity/Hall measurement system

SampleSize.description: mechanical testing samples were 70 mm long x 12.7 mm        wide
